[h1|ATTR]What are Attributes?[/h1]
[i]Attributes[/i] describe the physical and mental prowess of a creature. A high attribute represents a high degree of competency in the particular attribute.
[br]Attributes can be raised with [i]Attribute Points[/i] (AP). Each experience level grants a creature [section:clr-value]10[/section] AP.
[br]Raising an attribute requires AP equivalent to the target value. This means that raising an attribute from [section:clr-value]1[/section] to [section:clr-value]2[/section] requires [section:clr-value]2[/section] AP, while raising an attribute from [section:clr-value]13[/section] to [section:clr-value]14[/section] requires [section:clr-value]14[/section] AP. Naturally, this means that attibutes have to be raised sequentially – going from [section:clr-value]O[/section] to [section:clr-value]3[/section] would require a total of [section:clr-value]6[/section] AP.

[h1|MOD]What are modifiers?[/h1]
Most dice rolls do not consider the raw value of an attribute. Instead, they use [i]modifiers[/i] (usually denoted as [section:clr-attr]MOD[/section]). The attribute modifier increases by [section:clr-value]one[/section] for every [section:clr-value]two[/section] raw attribute points.
